[1
Date: 2 Mar 2001
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj@mail.vetmed.lsu.edu>
Source: The Times, 2 Mar 2001 [edited

Smuggler caused Ulster outbreak
------------------------------
A sheep and diesel smuggler operating along the Ulster border was being
blamed last night for the introduction of FMD to Ireland for the first time
in 60 years.
The first case of the disease was confirmed yesterday in the village of
Meigh in south Armagh. Noel Davern, the junior agriculture minister in the
Irish republic, said: "The danger now is not from the airports or anywhere
else, but from people who acted illegally in south Armagh."
The border between Ulster and the Irish Republic is rife with smuggling.
The IRA, at the height of the troubles, smuggled huge amounts of diesel
across the border to raise funds to buy weapons.
One man was arrested by the Royal Ulster Constabulary yesterday in
connection with alleged smuggling.
